Federal Emergency Management Agency (Photo credit: Wikipedia)
From the we‚Äôve been telling you so department, comes this honest briefing to the White House:
(CNSNews.com) ‚Äì Federal Emergency Management Agency Director Craig Fugate said the frequency of tornadoes and hurricanes is cyclical, and he doesn‚Äôt know if global warming has anything to do with it.

‚ÄúIf you look back for the amount information we have going back to about 1850s, you‚Äôll see a cycle, and it‚Äôs over decades of increased activity and decreased activity,‚Äù Fugate said. ‚ÄúAnd so that cycle has been there. As far anything driving that, I‚Äôd really defer to climate scientists.‚Äù
‚ÄúWell, I‚Äôm not a meteorologist. I‚Äôm not a climate scientist, and hurricanes are cyclic,‚Äù Fugate responded. ‚ÄúI do know history, and if you look at history and you look at hurricane activity, there are periods of increased and decreased activity that occurs over decades,‚Äù Fugate said. ‚ÄúThroughout the ‚Äò60s, ‚Äò70s, early ‚Äò80s, up until about ‚Äô95, the Atlantic was actually in a period of below-average activity, even though you had significant storms like Andrew, Frederic, and David.‚Äù
‚ÄúBeginning about 1995, we saw an uptick in activity that has been sustained, and about the only variation is whether or not we‚Äôve had El Ni√±os or La Ni√±as, depending upon that for a factor,‚Äù Fugate continued. ‚ÄúBut if you look back for the amount information we have going back to about 1850s, you‚Äôll see a cycle, and it‚Äôs over decades of increased activity and decreased activity. And so that cycle has been there. As far anything driving that, I‚Äôd really defer to climate scientists.‚Äù
‚ÄúBut the reality is the history says we‚Äôve had this period of activity, we‚Äôve had a period of quiet,‚Äù Fugate said. ‚ÄúWe‚Äôve had a period of activity; we‚Äôve had a period of quiet. And so what we‚Äôve seen is not what we ‚Äî we‚Äôve seen this in history before.‚Äù
Fugate spoke Wednesday at a White House press briefing on the 2012 hurricane season that begins June 1.
h/t to Climate Depot
